In your the given code snippet, a for loop is used to create and start multiple instances of a `MultithreadThing` object. Each time the loop iterates, a new instance of `MultithreadThing` is created, and its `start()` method is called, which typically starts a new thread of execution.

 1. Inside the loop body, a new instance of `MultithreadThing` is created using the `new` keyword. This creates a new object in memory.
 2. The `start()` method of the `MultithreadThing` object is called. Assuming the `start()` method is implemented to start a new thread as mentioned above, a new thread of execution is created and begins running concurrently with the main thread.
 3. The loop variable `i` is incremented.

the loop spawns multiple threads in parallel, and each thread will execute independently and concurrently with the main thread and other threads. The loop does not pause or wait for any thread to finish before proceeding to the next iteration.

If you want to wait for each task to complete before incrementing `i` and moving on to the next iteration of the loop, you can use something like [join()][1] method on each thread. The `join()` method blocks the execution of the calling thread until the thread it is called on completes.


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/package-summary.html

